{
  "In multivariate statistics, the covariance matrix of a random vector X = (X_1, ..., X_n) has entry C_ij = Cov(X_i, X_j). What type of matrix is C always?": "",
  "Symmetric positive semi-definite": "",
  "Diagonal": "",
  "Orthogonal": "",
  "Upper triangular": "",
  "The covariance matrix C is symmetric (Cov(X_i,X_j) = Cov(X_j,X_i)) and positive semi-definite (a^T C a = Var(a^T X) >= 0 for all a). It is positive definite if no linear combination of variables is deterministic.": "",
  "The correlation matrix R has entries R_ij = Cov(X_i, X_j) / (sigma_i * sigma_j). All diagonal entries of R are:": "",
  "sigma_i^2": "",
  "0": "",
  "1": "",
  "Variable, depending on the data": "",
  "R_ii = Cov(X_i, X_i) / (sigma_i * sigma_i) = sigma_i^2 / sigma_i^2 = 1. The correlation matrix is a standardized covariance matrix with all diagonal entries equal to 1.": "",
  "In linear regression y = X*beta + epsilon, the OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) estimator is beta_hat = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T y. This formula requires X^T X to be:": "",
  "Negative definite": "",
  "Invertible (full column rank in X)": "",
  "X^T X is invertible when X has full column rank (linearly independent columns/features). This ensures a unique least-squares solution. When columns are linearly dependent (multicollinearity), X^T X is singular.": "",
  "The hat matrix H = X(X^T X)^{-1} X^T in regression satisfies y_hat = Hy. What are two key properties of H?": "",
  "H is diagonal and positive definite": "",
  "H is symmetric and idempotent (H^2 = H)": "",
  "H is nilpotent and skew-symmetric": "",
  "H is orthogonal and invertible": "",
  "H is a projection matrix (orthogonal projection onto the column space of X). As such, H = H^T (symmetric) and H^2 = H (idempotent). Its eigenvalues are 0 and 1, and trace(H) = rank(X) = p.": "",
  "The multivariate normal distribution N(mu, Sigma) is parameterized by mean vector mu and covariance matrix Sigma. The density function involves which matrix operation on Sigma?": "",
  "Transpose of Sigma in most standard conditions": "",
  "Inversion: (x-mu)^T Sigma^{-1} (x-mu) appears in the exponent": "",
  "SVD of Sigma, particularly regarding": "",
  "Eigendecomposition of Sigma": "",
  "The density is proportional to exp(-1/2 (x-mu)^T Sigma^{-1} (x-mu)). The quadratic form (x-mu)^T Sigma^{-1} (x-mu) is the squared Mahalanobis distance, which accounts for correlations and different variances.": "",
  "In factor analysis, the observed variables X = Lambda*F + epsilon where Lambda is the loading matrix, F is the factor vector, and epsilon is noise. If there are 10 observed variables and 3 factors, what are the dimensions of Lambda?": "",
  "10 x 3": "",
  "3 x 10": "",
  "3 x 3": "",
  "10 x 10": "",
  "Lambda maps the 3 latent factors to the 10 observed variables, so Lambda is 10 x 3. Each column of Lambda shows how one factor influences all 10 variables.": "",
  "The Mahalanobis distance from a point x to a distribution with mean mu and covariance Sigma is d = sqrt((x-mu)^T Sigma^{-1} (x-mu)). Why is this preferred over Euclidean distance for outlier detection?": "",
  "It accounts for correlations between variables and different variances in each direction": "",
  "It is always smaller than Euclidean distance": "",
  "It can be computed without knowing the covariance": "",
  "It is rotation-invariant": "",
  "Mahalanobis distance normalizes by the covariance structure, so a point far from the mean in a low-variance direction is considered more unusual than one equally far in a high-variance direction. It transforms elliptical contours to spherical ones.": "",
  "In canonical correlation analysis (CCA), the goal is to find linear combinations of two sets of variables that are maximally correlated. This is solved as a generalized eigenvalue problem involving which matrices?": "",
  "The eigenvalues of each set separately": "",
  "The identity matrix and data matrix": "",
  "The inverse of the data matrix": "",
  "The cross-covariance and within-set covariance matrices": "",
  "CCA solves Sigma_xy Sigma_yy^{-1} Sigma_yx a = rho^2 Sigma_xx a, a generalized eigenvalue problem. The canonical correlations are the square roots of these eigenvalues, and the vectors a, b give the optimal linear combinations.": "",
  "The variance of a linear combination a^T X is Var(a^T X) = a^T Sigma a. For Sigma = [[4, 2], [2, 3]] and a = (1, -1), what is Var(a^T X)?": "",
  "5": "",
  "3": "",
  "7": "",
  "a^T Sigma a = [1,-1] [[4,2],[2,3]] [1,-1]^T = [1,-1] [4-2, 2-3]^T = [1,-1] [2, -1]^T = 2 + 1 = 3.": "",
  "Multicollinearity in regression occurs when predictor variables are highly correlated. How does this manifest in the matrix X^T X?": "",
  "X^T X becomes the identity, particularly regarding highly based on the": "",
  "X^T X becomes orthogonal, particularly regarding occurs in most standard conditions": "",
  "X^T X becomes nearly singular (has very small eigenvalues), making (X^T X)^{-1} unstable": "",
  "X^T X has all negative eigenvalues when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "Multicollinearity means columns of X are nearly linearly dependent, making X^T X nearly singular. Its small eigenvalues cause large entries in (X^T X)^{-1}, inflating the variance of beta_hat. The condition number of X^T X is high.": "",
  "What is the 'covariance matrix' in statistics?": "",
  "A diagonal matrix of means": "",
  "The inverse of the correlation matrix": "",
  "A symmetric matrix where entry (i,j) measures the linear relationship between variables i and j": "",
  "A matrix that counts covariant data points": "",
  "The covariance matrix Sigma has entry Sigma_ij = Cov(X_i, X_j) = E[(X_i - mu_i)(X_j - mu_j)]. Diagonal entries are variances, off-diagonal entries measure linear co-movement between variable pairs.": "",
  "What is 'multivariate normal distribution'?": "",
  "A normal distribution with multiple modes, particularly regarding joint following conventional understanding": "",
  "A distribution where each variable is independently normal as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "A distribution that applies to matrices, not vectors when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "A probability distribution for a vector of random variables where every linear combination is normally distributed, parameterized by mean vector and covariance matrix": "",
  "The multivariate normal N(mu, Sigma) is a joint distribution where any linear combination a^T X is univariate normal. It is completely determined by its mean vector mu and covariance matrix Sigma.": "",
  "What is 'principal component regression' (PCR)?": "",
  "Regression using only the first two variables": "",
  "Regression where the principal variable is the response": "",
  "Performing regression on the principal components of X instead of the original variables, to handle multicollinearity": "",
  "A nonlinear regression method": "",
  "PCR first applies PCA to X to get orthogonal principal components, then regresses y on the top k components. This eliminates multicollinearity (components are orthogonal) and removes noise in the low-variance directions.": "",
  "What does 'leverage' mean in regression, in terms of the hat matrix?": "",
  "The condition number of X, particularly regarding close based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The ratio of explained to total variance when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "The determinant of the hat matrix, particularly regarding does when evaluated systematically": "",
  "The diagonal entry h_ii of the hat matrix H, measuring how influential observation i is on its own fitted value": "",
  "The leverage h_ii = e_i^T H e_i measures how much observation i influences its own predicted value. High leverage points (h_ii close to 1) are far from the center of the predictor space and can unduly affect the regression.": "",
  "What is the 'precision matrix' (inverse covariance)?": "",
  "A matrix measuring the accuracy of each measurement": "",
  "Omega = Sigma^{-1}, where zero entries indicate conditional independence between variables": "",
  "The square of the covariance matrix": "",
  "The correlation matrix divided by sample size": "",
  "The precision matrix Omega = Sigma^{-1} directly encodes the conditional independence structure. If Omega_ij = 0, then X_i and X_j are conditionally independent given all other variables. This is central to graphical models.": "",
  "What is 'Hotelling's T-squared test'?": "",
  "A multivariate hypothesis test that generalizes the univariate t-test using the Mahalanobis distance: T^2 = n(x_bar - mu_0)^T S^{-1} (x_bar - mu_0)": "",
  "A test that only applies to 2x2 matrices, particularly regarding account when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A test for matrix singularity, particularly regarding equals according to conventional analysis": "",
  "A test that checks if two matrices are equal in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "Hotelling's T^2 tests whether a multivariate mean vector equals a hypothesized value. It uses the sample covariance matrix S to account for correlations, and follows an F-distribution under the null hypothesis.": "",
  "What is 'MANOVA' (Multivariate Analysis of Variance)?": "",
  "A multivariate regression technique": "",
  "A statistical test comparing mean vectors of multiple groups using matrices of between-group and within-group sums of squares": "",
  "An analysis of variance performed on each variable separately": "",
  "A method for computing the variance of a matrix": "",
  "MANOVA generalizes ANOVA to multiple dependent variables. It compares mean vectors using the ratio of between-group to within-group scatter matrices (B and W). Test statistics involve eigenvalues of W^{-1}B.": "",
  "What is the 'graphical lasso'?": "",
  "A technique for drawing graphs of matrix entries": "",
  "A visualization tool for lasso regression": "",
  "A method for estimating a sparse precision matrix by adding an L1 penalty on the off-diagonal entries of Omega": "",
  "A method for finding the shortest path in a graph": "",
  "The graphical lasso estimates the precision matrix Omega by maximizing the penalized log-likelihood: max [log det(Omega) - trace(S*Omega) - lambda * ||Omega||_1]. The L1 penalty encourages sparsity, revealing the conditional independence graph.": "",
  "What does 'shrinkage estimator' mean for covariance matrices?": "",
  "Dividing all covariance entries by the sample size according to conventional analysis": "",
  "An estimator that reduces the size of the matrix, particularly regarding blend when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "An estimator that removes variables with small variance under normal circumstances": "",
  "A regularized estimate that shrinks the sample covariance toward a structured target (like the identity), improving conditioning: Sigma_hat = alpha*S + (1-alpha)*T": "",
  "When n < p (more variables than samples), the sample covariance is singular. Shrinkage estimators blend the sample covariance S with a well-conditioned target T (like alpha*I): Sigma_hat = alpha*S + (1-alpha)*T.": "",
  "What is 'discriminant analysis' using linear algebra?": "",
  "A method for discriminating between good and bad data when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "A classification method that finds linear combinations of variables that best separate classes, using within-class and between-class scatter matrices": "",
  "Analyzing which eigenvalues are positive vs negative in the context of this analysis": "",
  "A technique for removing outliers, particularly regarding using as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "Linear discriminant analysis finds directions w that maximize the ratio w^T S_B w / w^T S_W w, where S_B is the between-class scatter matrix and S_W is the within-class scatter. This is a generalized eigenvalue problem.": "",
  "A medical researcher has measurements on 5 biomarkers for 200 patients. The sample covariance matrix S is 5x5. She wants to test if the population mean vector equals mu_0 = (10, 20, 30, 40, 50) using Hotelling's T^2. What distribution does the test statistic follow under H_0?": "",
  "A chi-squared distribution with 5 degrees of freedom": "",
  "A uniform distribution": "",
  "An F-distribution (after transformation) with p and n-p degrees of freedom (5 and 195)": "",
  "A normal distribution": "",
  "Under H_0, the transformed statistic [(n-p)/(p(n-1))] * T^2 follows an F(p, n-p) = F(5, 195) distribution. This accounts for the estimation uncertainty in both the mean and covariance.": "",
  "A financial analyst estimates the covariance matrix of 100 stock returns using 60 trading days of data. Why is the sample covariance matrix problematic?": "",
  "With n = 60 < p = 100, the sample covariance is singular (rank at most 59) and cannot be inverted": "",
  "Stock returns don't have a covariance following the established framework": "",
  "It will be too small, particularly regarding data as predicted by standard models": "",
  "60 days is too much data for 100 stocks when evaluated systematically": "",
  "The sample covariance matrix with n observations and p variables has rank at most min(n-1, p) = 59. Since 59 < 100, the matrix is singular (rank-deficient) and its inverse doesn't exist. Shrinkage or factor models are needed.": "",
  "A social scientist uses factor analysis on 20 survey questions and finds that 3 factors explain 80% of the variance. The loading matrix Lambda is 20x3. If the factor scores F = (1.5, -0.5, 0.8) and the first row of Lambda is (0.8, 0.1, 0.3), what is the model's prediction for variable 1?": "",
  "1.5 - 0.5 + 0.8 = 1.8": "",
  "1.5 + 0.8 = 2.3": "",
  "0.8(1.5) + 0.1(-0.5) + 0.3(0.8) = 1.39": "",
  "0.8 * 0.1 * 0.3 = 0.024": "",
  "X_1 = Lambda_1 . F = 0.8(1.5) + 0.1(-0.5) + 0.3(0.8) = 1.20 - 0.05 + 0.24 = 1.39. This is the dot product of the first row of the loading matrix with the factor score vector.": "",
  "A data scientist computes the sample correlation matrix of 4 variables and finds eigenvalues 2.5, 1.0, 0.4, 0.1. How many principal components should she retain using the 'eigenvalue > 1' (Kaiser) criterion?": "",
  "2 (eigenvalues 2.5 and 1.0 are >= 1)": "",
  "3 (the first three eigenvalues)": "",
  "1 (only eigenvalue 2.5 exceeds 1)": "",
  "4 (all eigenvalues)": "",
  "The Kaiser criterion retains components with eigenvalues >= 1 (for a correlation matrix, where the average eigenvalue is 1). Eigenvalues 2.5 and 1.0 meet this criterion, so retain 2 components. They explain (2.5 + 1.0)/4 = 87.5% of variance.": "",
  "A geneticist uses MANOVA to test whether 3 genetic groups differ in their mean vectors across 10 gene expression measurements. The Wilks' Lambda statistic involves the determinant of which matrices?": "",
  "Lambda = det(X^T X), particularly regarding lambda as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Lambda = det(B) / det(W), particularly regarding matrices under normal circumstances": "",
  "Lambda = trace(W) / trace(B) within the typical range of values": "",
  "Lambda = det(W) / det(W + B), where W is within-group and B is between-group scatter matrix": "",
  "Wilks' Lambda = det(W)/det(W+B) measures how much of the total variation is within-group vs between-group. Small Lambda (close to 0) means groups differ significantly. It is related to the eigenvalues of W^{-1}B.": "",
  "A marketing analyst uses canonical correlation analysis between 5 customer demographic variables (X) and 3 purchase behavior variables (Y). What is the maximum number of canonical correlations?": "",
  "5 (the maximum of the two set sizes)": "",
  "15 (the product)": "",
  "3 (the minimum of the two set sizes)": "",
  "8 (the sum)": "",
  "The number of canonical correlations equals min(p, q) = min(5, 3) = 3. Each canonical correlation is the maximum correlation between a linear combination of X and a linear combination of Y, subject to orthogonality constraints.": "",
  "A bioinformatician analyzes gene expression with p = 20,000 genes and n = 50 samples. She estimates the precision matrix using the graphical lasso. The sparsity pattern of the estimated precision matrix reveals:": "",
  "The marginal correlation between all gene pairs as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "The conditional independence structure -- a gene regulatory network where edges represent direct interactions": "",
  "Which samples are outliers, particularly regarding indicate under the given assumptions": "",
  "Which genes are most expressed, particularly regarding with when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Nonzero entries in the precision matrix indicate conditional dependence (direct interaction). The graphical lasso encourages sparsity, revealing only the strongest direct gene-gene interactions and filtering out indirect correlations.": "",
  "A psychometrician applies confirmatory factor analysis to a 30-item test and hypothesizes 5 factors. She constrains certain entries of the loading matrix Lambda (30x5) to zero based on theory. Why is this different from exploratory factor analysis?": "",
  "They are the same method with different names": "",
  "Confirmatory FA tests a specific hypothesized structure with constrained loadings, while exploratory FA estimates all loadings freely": "",
  "Confirmatory FA uses eigenvalues and exploratory FA does not": "",
  "Confirmatory FA only works with 2 factors": "",
  "In confirmatory FA, the researcher specifies which items load on which factors (setting some Lambda entries to zero). This tests whether the hypothesized structure fits the observed covariance matrix, unlike exploratory FA which freely estimates all loadings.": "",
  "A quality control engineer monitors p = 8 process variables using multivariate control charts. She uses the T^2 statistic based on the Mahalanobis distance. If a new observation has T^2 = 25 and the 99% control limit is 20.1, what action should she take?": "",
  "Recalculate the covariance matrix": "",
  "Increase the number of monitored variables": "",
  "No action needed, the process is in control": "",
  "Investigate the process, as T^2 = 25 exceeds the control limit of 20.1, indicating an out-of-control condition": "",
  "Since T^2 = 25 > 20.1 (the 99% limit), the observation is statistically unusual at the 1% significance level. This signals that the multivariate process has shifted from its in-control state and needs investigation.": "",
  "A climate scientist models 50 years of monthly temperature data at 100 weather stations using a space-time covariance matrix. The matrix is 6000 x 6000 (100 stations x 60 months). What technique can make this tractable?": "",
  "Ignoring all off-diagonal entries, particularly regarding covariance under normal circumstances": "",
  "Using only 2 weather stations, particularly regarding climate following the established framework": "",
  "Assuming separable space-time structure: Sigma = Sigma_space (x) Sigma_time, reducing to a 100x100 and 60x60 matrix": "",
  "Replacing the covariance with the identity as predicted by standard models": "",
  "The separability assumption Sigma = Sigma_space (x) Sigma_time (Kronecker product) reduces estimation from 6000^2/2 ~ 18 million parameters to 100^2/2 + 60^2/2 ~ 6,800 parameters. The Kronecker structure also enables efficient computation.": ""
